Overview of RStudio

The 4 main panes in RStudio are as follows:

Source Pane (top-left)

This is where you write and edit your R scripts. These scripts are able to be saved and re-used as .R files. Note: the source pane will not be visible if you do not have an R script open.

Console Pane (bottom-left)

This is the interactive R console where you can execute R commands directly. Any outputs from the source pane code will appear in the console pane. It will also display any warnings or error messages in the console. While the Console Pane is great for quick tests, remember that code executed here is not saved. For reproducibility, it’s best to write and save your code in the Source Pane. It is useful for quick calculations, testing snippets of code, and debugging.

Environment Pane (top-right)

This displays all the objects (e.g., data frames, vectors, functions) currently in your R environment. It allows you to view and manage your workspace. Things in the environment are temporarily stored there during your R working session, but when you close R these will disappear. It is important to have R scripts that are saved so you can easily reload your objects into your environment for each session.

Files/Plots/Packages/Help Pane (bottom right)

We mostly only use the Plots and Help tabs here, but there are other tabs (files for file management but I prefer to use the computer file management for this & packages which shows you which packages are currently being used). The Plots tab displays plots generated by your R code and has options to export plots and navigate through multiple plots. The Help tab is where you can search for help on functions and packages. You can access the help tab from your Source Pane by typing ? followed by the function name you want to learn more about. For example, typing ?mean in your script or console will open the help page for the mean function in the Help tab.

?mean

Simple customizations in RStudio

Soft-wrap source files

Soft-wrapping allows long lines of code to wrap onto the next line within the Source Pane without inserting actual line breaks in the code. This feature helps you view entire lines of code without horizontal scrolling. To enable: Go to Tools > Global Options > Code > Editing and check the option for “Soft-wrap R source files”

Rainbow parentheses

Rainbow parentheses color-code matching pairs of parentheses, brackets, and braces. This visual aid helps you easily identify matching pairs, especially in complex expressions or nested functions. To enable: Go to Tools > Global Options > Code > Display and check the option for “Use rainbow parentheses”

Highlight R function calls

Highlighting R function calls visually distinguishes function names from other code elements. This feature can make it easier to identify where functions are being used in your scripts. To enable: Go to Tools > Global Options > Code > Display. Check the option for “Highlight R function calls”

Aesthetics

You can customize the overall look and feel of the interface by navigating to Tools > Global Options > Appearance. Here you can choose from a variety of editor themes to change how your code looks as well as adjust font type and size.

Basic Operations

Create a New R Script

Navigate to the top menu and click on File > New File > R Script. This will open a new script editor in the Source Pane. Avoid saving your scripts (.R files) to temporary or cloud-based locations where they might be difficult to retrieve later. Instead, choose a well-organized folder on your local machine or a reliable cloud storage service with clear navigation. You should create a dedicated folder for your R projects to keep your scripts and related files organized.

Running code from the script in the console

  • Run a Single Line: Place your cursor on the line you want to run and click the Run button at the top of the script editor, or press Ctrl + Enter (Windows/Linux) or Cmd + Enter (Mac).
  • Run Multiple Lines: Highlight the lines you want to run and click the Run button or use the same keyboard shortcut.

Remember the code you execute, even in the Source Pane, will always be displayed in the Console Pane.

Examples of running code

Assigning variables

You can assign a value to a variable using the assignment operator <-, which is the most common and recommended method in R. Avoid using the = operator, despite it working similarly, because <- is preferred for clarity and convention.

# Assigns the numeric value 10 to the variable x
x <- 10  
# Assigns the character string "Alice" to the variable name
name <- "Alice"  
# Assigns the logical value TRUE to the variable is_active
is_active <- TRUE

Once a variable is assigned, it automatically appears in the Environment Pane and can be used in operations:

a <- 10
b <- 5

a + b
## [1] 15
a * b
## [1] 50
a / b
## [1] 2
a - b
## [1] 5
c <- a + b^2
  • Naming Conventions: Variable names should be descriptive and can include letters, numbers, underscores, and periods. They must start with a letter or a period followed by a letter.
  • Case Sensitivity: R is case-sensitive, meaning myVar and myvar would be considered different variables.
  • Reassignment: Variables can be reassigned to new values at any time, allowing for dynamic data manipulation.

Removing variables from the environment

The rm() function in R is used to remove objects from your environment. This function is particularly useful for managing memory and keeping your environment organized by deleting variables or data structures that are no longer needed.

rm(c)

Vectors and c()

A vector is a data structure that holds elements of the SAME TYPE. Vectors are used to store and manipulate collections of data, such as numbers, characters, or logical values. The c() function, which stands for “combine” or “concatenate,” is the primary way to create vectors in R.

numeric_vector <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
char_vector <- c("apple", "banana", "cherry")
logical_vector <- c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE)

KEY POINT! VERY IMPORTANT TO REMEMBER All elements in a vector must be of the same type!!!! If you mix types, R will coerce them to a common type, usually converting everything to character.

mixed_vector <- c("bonaire", "moorea", "adam", 2)  # All elements become character

Functions

Functions in R are reusable blocks of code designed to perform specific tasks. They take inputs, known as arguments, process them, and return outputs. Remember you can use ? to search for the help file on functions, which will have a list of the arguments it takes.

numbers <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)

# mean() : calculates the average of a numeric vector
average <- mean(numbers)  

# sum() : computes the total sum of elements in a numeric vector
total <- sum(numbers)

Miscellaneous things we touched on WEEK 1

  • Be careful when naming your variables that you aren’t overwriting something already in R - if you assign a variable with the same name as one of these functions, you temporarily overwrite the function in your current session.

  • Colon operator: generates a vector containing a series of integers from a starting value to an ending value, inclusive. This operator is often used for creating simple sequences and iterating over ranges in loops.

Week 2

Understanding R Packages

In R, packages are collections of functions, data, and compiled code that extend the base functionality of R. You can make your own package if you wanted to!

  • Packages provide specialized functions that are not available in base R.
  • Many packages are developed and maintained by others in the R world—this can be good or bad depending on how well they are updated and maintained.
  • Leveraging existing packages can significantly reduce the time and effort required to implement complex analyses.

Loading Packages

To install a package, use the install.packages() function:

install.packages("tidyverse")

This is a one-time action, typically done per R installation or when updating a package.

Once installed, load the package into your R session with library():

library(tidyverse)

Key Points:

  • You need to load the package for each new R session.
  • Even after installation, a package’s functions remain inaccessible until explicitly loaded.
  • Loading packages consumes memory, so only load what you need.

Function Name Clashes

Loading multiple packages that have functions with the same name can lead to conflicts. Use the :: operator to specify which function to use:

library(dplyr)
library(MASS) # Both have a 'select' function

dplyr::select(data, column)
MASS::select(data, column)

Using namespace prefixes can reduce memory usage and prevent function conflicts.

You can cite packages you use in papers/methods sections

citation("tidyverse")



Data Types in R

  • Numeric: Represents numbers (e.g., 42, 3.14)
  • Character: Strings of text (e.g., “Hello”)
  • Logical: Boolean values (TRUE, FALSE)
num <- 13

Reading Data into R

File Pathways

To load a file into R, specify the correct file path.

File pathway on Mac

Using Finder:

  • Open Finder and navigate to the file whose path you want to copy.
  • Right-click (or Control-click) on the file.
  • Hold down the Option key, and you will see the “Copy” option change to “Copy [file name] as Pathname.”
  • Click on “Copy [file name] as Pathname” to copy the full file path to your clipboard.

File pathway on PC

Using File Explorer:

  • Open File Explorer and navigate to the file whose path you want to copy.
  • Right-click on the file while holding the Shift key.
  • Select “Copy as path” from the context menu. This will copy the full file path to your clipboard.

Using the Address Bar:

  • Navigate to the folder containing your file in File Explorer.
  • Click on the address bar to reveal the full path.
  • You can then manually append the file name to the path if needed.

CSV format

A CSV (Comma-Separated Values) file is a simple text format used to store tabular data. Each line in a CSV file represents a row in the table, and each value within the row is separated by a comma.

Why Use CSV Files?

  • CSV files are plain text, making them easy to create and edit with any text editor. They do not require special software to open, unlike proprietary formats like Excel.
  • CSV files are supported by almost all data processing software, including spreadsheets, databases, and programming languages.
  • CSV files are lightweight and have a smaller file size compared to formats that include additional metadata or formatting, such as Excel. This can lead to faster data processing and reduced storage requirements.

Saving an excel file as a CSV

Steps to Save as CSV:

  1. Open the Excel File: Launch Microsoft Excel and open the workbook you want to convert to a CSV file.
  2. Select the Worksheet: Ensure that the worksheet you want to save as a CSV is active. Note that only the active worksheet will be saved in the CSV format.
  3. Save As CSV:
  • Click on File in the menu bar.
  • Select Save As or Save a Copy (depending on your version of Excel).
  • Choose the location where you want to save the file.
  • In the Save as type dropdown menu, select CSV (Comma delimited) (*.csv).
  • Enter a name for your file and click Save.
  1. Confirm and Close: Excel may prompt you with a warning that some features in your workbook might be lost if you save it as a CSV. This is because CSV files do not support multiple sheets, formulas, or formatting. Click OK to proceed. You will NOT lose your excel file!

Loading Data

It’s important to give your dataframe a descriptive name that reflects its contents, rather than a generic name like ‘data’. For naming conventions, it is common to use underscores (_) when naming objects in your environment. Function names usually use dots (.) - example: install.packages(). Be consistent in your work!

The $ operator allows you to access a specific column from a dataframe. Since each column in a dataframe is essentially a vector, using $ lets you extract that column and work with it as a standalone vector.

Notice that RStudio’s auto-complete feature can help you fill in column names after typing the $ symbol.

bonaire_fish_counts  # Displays the entire dataframe

The output in the console can be difficult to read, especially if there are many species and sites. To make it easier to work with, we can save the table as an object in our environment.

species_by_site <- table(bonaire_fish_counts$Species, bonaire_fish_counts$Site)

By saving the table as an object, it appears in the ‘Values’ section of our R environment. However, it can still only be viewed in a matrix-like format in the console, which still sucks :(

We can convert the table to a dataframe for easier viewing and manipulation using as.data.frame()

species_by_site_df <- as.data.frame(species_by_site)

Alternatively, you can replace the original table object with the dataframe object by naming it the same thing:

species_by_site <- as.data.frame(species_by_site)

By reassigning the dataframe to the original object name, we maintain a single object in our environment, helping to keep the workspace organized and not bloated

Table vs. Dataframe:

  • Dataframes are more flexible and easier to manipulate, allowing for operations like filtering and sorting
  • A table object is a matrix-like structure that is efficient for counting and summarizing data.
  • A dataframe object is more versatile, allowing for operations like filtering and sorting
# Frequency of species by site and stage
species_site_stage_count <- table(bonaire_fish_counts$Site, 
                                  bonaire_fish_counts$Species, 
                                  bonaire_fish_counts$Stage)
species_site_stage_count <- as.data.frame(species_site_stage_count)

quick tip: I like to add a line break after commas within functions because it is enhances readability:

#without line breaks
result <- some_function(arg1, arg2, arg3, arg4, arg5)

# with line breaks
result <- some_function(
    arg1,
    arg2,
    arg3,
    arg4,
    arg5
)

Proportions

The prop.table() function converts frequency tables into proportions to understand relative frequencies.

species_proportion <- prop.table(table(bonaire_fish_counts$Species))
species_proportion <- as.data.frame(species_proportion)

Date Conversion

Turning a date or time column into a date-time format instead of character using as.POSIXct() ensures consistency and allows for calculations and comparisons.

bonaire_fish_counts$Date <- as.POSIXct(bonaire_fish_counts$Date, format = "%m/%d/%y")

Explanation of the format argument:

  • %m: Month as a decimal number (01-12)
  • %d: Day of the month as a decimal number (01-31)
  • %y: Year without century (00-99)

This format string tells R how to interpret the components of the date character string

Notice we are assigning new data to a column using the same column name meaning we are effectively overwrite the existing data in that column. This operation updates the dataframe in place, replacing the old values with the new ones.


Basic Statistics

mean size of fish

mean(bonaire_fish_counts$Size)
## [1] NA

Notice how it returns an NA value - NAs are trump cards, if there is an NA in your column when you are trying to do these basic summary stats, it will always return an NA!

use na.rm: this argument stands for “NA remove” and is used to specify whether NA values should be removed before performing the calculation

setting na.rm = TRUE tells the function to ignore NA values and compute the mean using only the available (non-missing) data.

mean(bonaire_fish_counts$Size, na.rm =TRUE)
## [1] 16.45634

standard deviation of fish size

sd(bonaire_fish_counts$Size, na.rm=TRUE)

minimum / maximum of fish size

max(bonaire_fish_counts$Size, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 41

median size of fish

median(bonaire_fish_counts$Size, na.rm=TRUE)

number of elements in a vector

Effectively this is just the number of rows/observations, so it isn’t too useful on it’s own often, but I will use it in the context of other tasks (for loops) or functions

Tidyverse

The tidyverse is a package of R packages designed for data science. The tidyverse is built around the concept of “tidy data,” where each variable is a column, each observation is a row, and each type of observational unit forms a table.

  • The tidyverse includes a suite of packages that work seamlessly together, such as dplyr for data manipulation, ggplot2 for data visualization, tidyr for data tidying, and readr for data import.

Piping with %>%: The magrittr package, part of the tidyverse, introduces the pipe operator %>%. It allows you to write cleaner and more readable code by chaining together a sequence of operations.

  • pipe operator shortcut on mac: Command + Shift + M
  • pipe operator shortcut on pc: Ctrl + Shift + M

What is %>% Piping? Imagine you have a series of tasks you need to perform on a dataset, like filtering, selecting columns, and summarizing data. You could write these tasks as separate steps, each one modifying the data and then passing it to the next step.

The pipe operator %>% lets you connect these steps in a single, continuous flow, making your code look more like a series of instructions.

  • Think of it as “then”: The %>% operator can be read as “then.” It takes the output of one function and passes it as the input to the next function. This makes it easy to follow the sequence of operations.
#install.packages("tidyverse")
library(tidyverse)

Create a data frame of princess parrotfish that are larger than 10cm.

There are multiple ways to do this:

I prefer to make each filter it’s own line - this allows for easier readability in my opinoin and if you decide to change what you are filtering out, you can easily comment out a line:
big_ole_princess <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    filter(Size > 10) %>%
    filter(Species == "Princess parrrotfish")

big_ole_princess <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    #filter(Size > 10) %>%
    filter(Species == "Princess parrrotfish")
You can also use operators like & (and) and | (or) to combine multiple conditions in a single filter
  • The & operator is used to apply both conditions simultaneously.
  • The | operator can be used to apply either condition.
big_ole_princess <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    filter(Size > 10 & Species == "Princess parrrotfish")
Create a dataframe that is fish greater than 10 cm OR any princess parrofish (regardless of size)
princess_OR_big_ole_fish <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    filter(Size > 10 | Species == "Princess parrrotfish")

Adding a New Column

The mutate() function in the dplyr package allows you to add new columns or modify existing columns in a data frame while retaining the rest of your data structure.

Here’s some generic syntax, but note that these are just examples, there are many ways to mutate a column using all the functions available to you!

## create a new column with new data
original_df <- original_df %>%
    mutate(new_column1 = new_data) 

## create a new column based on some expression involving existing columns
original_df <- original_df %>%
    mutate(new_column2 = old_column1 + oldcolumn2)

## create a new column based on some function on another column
original_df <- original_df %>%
    mutate(new_column3 = mean(old_column4))

## modify an existing column (this replaces the old data in that column)
original_df <- original_df %>%
    mutate(old_column = 10 * old_column)

Using our data:

## Creates a new column called `index` that gives each row a unique number value
bonaire_fish_counts <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    mutate(index = 1:nrow(bonaire_fish_counts))

## Creates a new column called `observer` that takes the first two characters of the character strings in the Survey_code column
bonaire_fish_counts <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    mutate(observer = substr(Survey_code, 1, 2))

## Creates a new column called `size_mm` that is the Size column multiplying by 10
bonaire_fish_counts <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    mutate(size_mm = Size * 10)

Notice that I am not creating a new dataframe each time because I just want my new columns in my existing dataframe, unless I am overwriting a column (which I probably wouldn’t do)

Grouping and Summarizing Data

In dplyr, group_by() is used to split your dataset into groups based on one or more columns.

You then use summarize() (or summarise()) to reduce each group to a single row by applying summary functions (e.g., mean(), sum(), n()).

This combination allows you to swiftly aggregate data, like counting the number of observations per group or calculating a group-specific average.

Examples of grouping variables:

  • Category/Type (e.g. species, treatment)
  • Site/Location
  • Time Period (e.g., year, month)
  • Demographics (e.g., sex, age group)

Here’s a generic syntax example:

summarized_df <- original_df %>%
  group_by(group_column1, 
           group_column2) %>%
  summarize(summary_stat_column1 = function(column_to_summarize1),
            summary_stat_solumn2 = function(column_to_summarize2))

Because you are reducing your data to the number of rows equivalent to your unique groupings, make sure you are saving it as a new summarized_df

Average Size by Species

avg_size <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%

Counting Observations

The function n() is used to count the number of observations in each group within the summarize() function. It simply returns the total number of rows in the group.

Number of Rows Per Species per Site

number_of_rows <- bonaire_fish_counts %>% 
    group_by(Site, 
             Species) %>% 
    summarize(count = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Site'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

NOTE: This is not the sum of all the fish seen at that site, because it is simply counting the rows within the group of Site - Species. So I may have 3 observations of banded butterflyfish at Angel City, but within those 3 observations the I have 2 fish at 5 cm, 1 fish at 6cm, and 3 at 7cm. n() would return the number 3, while sum(Number) would return the number 6.

Unique Species Count per Site

The function n_distinct() counts the number of unique values in a column for each group. It is useful when you want to know how many distinct entries exist in a column, like for us species richness:

species_richness_per_site <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    group_by(Site) %>%
    summarize(unique_species_count = n_distinct(Species))

You can stack multiple summary functions:

summarized_df <- bonaire_fish_counts %>% 
    group_by(Site, 
             Species) %>% 
    summarize(avg_fish_size_cm = mean(Size, na.rm = TRUE),
              sd_fish_size_cm = sd(Size, na.rm = TRUE),
              fish_abundance = sum(Number, na.rm = TRUE))

summarized_df <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%

             Species) %>%

              sd_fish_size_cm = sd(Size, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Site'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Remember that when you combine group_by() with summarize(), the result is a new data frame which, by default, only contains:

  • The grouping columns specified in group_by().

  • The newly created summary columns from summarize().

All non-grouping columns that are not summarized will be dropped in the result.

If you want to keep certain columns that aren’t directly summarized, you need to include them in group_by() (making them part of the grouping). That way, those columns will be preserved in the group-level output. Just make sure that it doesn’t split you into more groups than you intend.

#Creates a character vector named fish_to_remove. It lists all the fish species you don’t want in your final dataframe.
fish_to_remove <- c("Eagle ray", 
                    "Eel", 
                    "Squid", 
                    "Turtle", 
                    "Hamlet", 
                    "Goldentail moray")

# The condition !(Species %in% fish_to_remove) means: keep rows where Species is not found in the fish_to_remove list.
# Excludes rows that contain any of the species in fish_to_remove
cleaned_data <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    filter(!(Species %in% fish_to_remove))

The %in% operator checks whether each element of a vector is found in another vector or list. It returns a logical vector of the same length as the first vector, indicating TRUE for every element that matches something in the second vector, and FALSE if it does not.

Essentially, it is assigning a TRUE or FALSE to every element in the column Species about whether or not that element matches an element in fish_to_remove. Usually, everything that is a FALSE is filtered out, which would leave us with only the rows where a Species column character string matched something (what we don’t want). By wrapping Species %in% fish_to_remove in !() we reverse the TRUE or FALSE , which then keeps only the rows where a Species column character string did NOT match something (what we DO want)

For the filter() function, it is always doing this - you provide a condition (size >10 or species = “parrotfish”) to which it assigns a TRUE or FALSE value and then keeps only TRUE values.

Why Use ggplot2?

Sequence with seq()

Random Sampling with sample()

The sample() function draws random values from a vector.

Here’s the syntax with the arguments explained:

sample(element_to_sample_over, size_of_sample, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL)

  • element_to_sample_over: vector of elements you will sample over (this can be a vector you made or a column in a dataframe)

  • size_of_sample: number of elements to sample from x

  • replace: logical value saying whether to sample with replacement (TRUE) or without replacement (FALSE) - the default is to sample without replacement

  • prob: a vector of probability weights for each element of x. If not specifying, each element has an equal probability - needs to be same length as the vector x!!

Here’s some examples:

sample(1:60, 15)
##  [1] 41 33 30 43 38 16 36 50 20  4  2 39 12 28 54
#sample(1:10, 15) ##this won't work because you are taking more objects than are in the vector without replacement
sample(1:10, 15, replace = TRUE)
##  [1]  2  1  1  8  7  3  2  8  8 10  3  4  5  2 10
sample(c("a", "b", "c"), 15, replace = TRUE, prob = c(2,1,1))
##  [1] "b" "a" "a" "c" "b" "a" "b" "a" "a" "a" "a" "a" "a" "a" "c"

In the last example, "a" becomes 2 times more likely to be randomly sampled than "b" or "c"

Miscellaneous Week 5 things

Positional vs. Specified Arguments in R Functions

In R, function arguments can be passed either by position (positional arguments) or by name (specified arguments):

  • Positional Arguments: You supply values in the exact order that the function definition expects them.

    • For example, if you have:
     myfun <- function(a, b, c) { 
       ...
     }

You might write it with your arguments as myfun(1, 2, 3). The first value goes to a, the second to b, and the third to c. So you don’t have to specify : function( a = 1, b = 2, c = 3)

  • Specified (Named) Arguments : You explicitly name each argument, so the order does not matter.
myfun(a = 1, c = 3, b = 2)

Why it matters:

  • Clarity: Specifying some arguments by name makes code more readable.

  • Flexibility: You can omit some default arguments or pass them in a different order.

  • Caution: R tries to match arguments by name first, then by position. If you rely on partial name matching, it can sometimes cause unexpected behavior. Best practice is to fully spell out named arguments where clarity is important, but notice when you can omit too

Notes on Coding Style

“Hard coding” means directly writing fixed values or data into the source code of a program, while “soft coding” refers to storing data or configuration information in a separate location (like a configuration file or database) and accessing it at runtime, allowing for easier modification without changing the core code itself; essentially, hard coding is less flexible but simpler, while soft coding provides greater adaptability and customization

Example, I want to create a random fake dataset with an arbitrary length of observations. I originally choose a length of 50

my_cute_vector <- seq(0.1, 2.9, length.out = 50)

However, because my choice was arbitrary, there is a good chance I may want to re-run this with a different number of observations, say 100:

my_cute_vector <- seq(0.1, 2.9, length.out = 100)

Instead of “hard coding” that number in the length.out = spot, and changing it, I can soft code it by assigning that value a name in my environment and then I just have to change that at the top and it will change in my function. This is especially useful when your number appears in multiple lines of code:

length_of_observations <- 100
my_cute_vector <- seq(0.1, 2.9, length.out = length_of_observations)

Activity #1 : T-test and ANOVAs with plots

T-TEST : Objective 1

# Filter the data to be just one species and two sites

fish_species <- c("Stoplight parrotfish")

sites <- c("SaltPier","AngelCity")

species_data <- bonaire_fish_counts %>% 
    filter(Species %in% fish_species, 
           Site %in% sites)

species_data <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    filter(Species %in% c("Stoplight parrotfish"))%>%
    filter(Site %in% c("SaltPier", "AngelCity"))

species_data <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    filter(Species == "Stoplight parrotfish")%>%
    filter(Site == "SaltPier"  | Site == "AngelCity")

Notice how there are multiple ways to accomplish the same task, some involve creating vectors outside the filter function, some involve using logic statements (or and and) to filter. All methods work fine, just be consistent in your work!

Note: The operator %in% is used to check if the elements of one vector are present in another vector, assigning a TRUE or FALSE value based on whether that element is present in the vector/column you are interested in

Syntax for using t.test() which is part of Base R:

t.test(numeric_variable ~ grouping_variable, data = your_data_frame)

Remember for a t-test you need some numeric variable that has been measured in some way (e.g., size, weight, count) that you want to test if the mean is different between two categorical groups (e.g., sex, site, treatment).

For our data we are curious about size (numeric variable) differences between two sites (categorical variable):

t_test_results <- t.test(Size ~ Site, data = species_data)
t_test_results
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Size by Site
## t = -0.63252, df = 57.49, p-value = 0.5296
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group AngelCity and group SaltPier is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -3.909630  2.032389
## sample estimates:
## mean in group AngelCity  mean in group SaltPier 
##                21.82000                22.75862

Understanding R’s t.test() Output:

  • Test Name: (e.g., Welch Two Sample t-test, Two Sample t-test, Paired t-test)

    • Tells you what version of the test you ran - R defaults to “Welch” version for two independent samples, which doesn’t assume equal variances between groups

    • YOU NEED TO UNDERSTAND THE UNDERLYING TEST AND ASSUMPTIONS IN ORDER TO ACCURATELY PERFORM STATS!!

  • data: (e.g., Size by Site in our example above)

    • reminds you which variables and grouping factors from the dataframe were used (e.g., comparing the Size variable between different levels of the Site factor)

  • t = ... (The t-statistic)

    • calculated value of the test statistic

    • stats specific info: this represents the difference between the sample means, measured in units of standard error. The further this value is from zero (either positive or negative), the less likely the observed difference is due to random chance alone if the null hypothesis were true

  • df = ... (Degrees of Freedom)

    • Degrees of freedom relate to the sample size(s) available to estimate population parameters

    • For a t-test, df is used along with the t-statistic to find the p-value.

    • NOTE: For a Welch test, df might not be a whole number.

  • p-value = ... (The P-value)

    • This is the probability of observing a t-statistic as extreme as, or more extreme than, the one calculated from your sample, assuming that the null hypothesis is actually true (i.e., assuming there’s no real difference between the population means)

  • alternative hypothesis: ...

    • This explicitly states the alternative hypothesis being tested against the null hypothesis. Common forms include:

      • true difference in means is not equal to 0 (two-sided test, default)

      • true difference in means is greater than 0 (one-sided test)

      • true difference in means is less than 0 (one-sided test)

  • 95 percent confidence interval:

    • Provides a range of values within which the true difference between the population means is likely to lie, with 95% confidence

    • stats specific info: If this interval does not contain zero, it’s further evidence against the null hypothesis (of no difference) at the 0.05 significance level (for a 95% CI)

  • sample estimates: (e.g., mean in group AngelCity, mean in group SaltPier)

    • These are the calculated means of your outcome variable (e.g., Size) for each of the groups defined by your grouping variable (e.g., Site) based on your sample data.

    • NOTE: For a paired test, it would show the mean of the differences.

Graphing for a t-test

The best graph for a t-test (or ANOVA) would be a point plot, where the point represents the mean and then has standard error bars

However, that’s actually a little tricky in R because we would have to boil down the information into a separate dataframe. I’ll include the code below for this but without going through it step-by-step.

Another perfectly acceptable way to represent data would be boxplots. The main issue with boxplots is that it really represents the median and not the mean (which is actually being compared in a t-test):

ggplot(species_data, aes(x = Site, y = Size)) +
    geom_boxplot(fill = c("aquamarine", "orange"))+
    theme_classic() +
    labs(x = "Site", 
         y = "Size")

Here’s the code to create the point plot with standard error. Notice you have to create a standard error function:

# Create standard error function
calculate_se <- function(x) {
    # Remove NA values
    x <- na.omit(x)
    # Calculate standard error: sd/sqrt(n)
    sd(x) / sqrt(length(x))
}


# Calculate mean and standard error for each site using calculate_se function
summary_data <- species_data %>%
    group_by(Site) %>%
    summarise(
        mean_size = mean(Size, na.rm = TRUE),
        se = calculate_se(Size),
        n = n()
    )

# Create the plot
ggplot(summary_data, aes(x = Site, y = mean_size)) +
    geom_point(size = 3,
               color = c("aquamarine", "orange")) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_size - se, ymax = mean_size + se), 
                 width = 0.2,
                 lwd = 1,
                 color = c("aquamarine", "orange")) +
    theme_classic() +
    labs(
        x = "Site",
        y = "Mean Size (cm)"
    )

ANOVA: Objective 2

An ANOVA is essentially an extension of a t-test with more than two groups. This means we still just want to filter to one species, but we can keep all 7 sites:

# Filter the data to be just one species

fish_species <- c("Stoplight parrotfish")

species_data2 <- bonaire_fish_counts %>% 
    filter(Species %in% fish_species)

species_data2 <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%

Syntax for using aov() which is part of Base R:

Luckily, the syntax for aov() is the same as the syntax for t.test()

  • Note: aov = analysis of variance
aov(numeric_variable ~ grouping_variable, data = your_data_frame)

The only difference is now you can have more than two groups to compare.

For our data we are curious about size (numeric variable) differences between all 7 sites (categorical variable):

anova_result <- aov(Size ~ Site, data = species_data2)
anova_result

Notice the difference between running anova_result and summary(anova_result):

  • Printing anova_result just gives you a basic description of the fitted model object.

  • Printing summary(anova_result) gives you the actual ANOVA results table with the statistics (F-value, p-value) you need to draw conclusions from your analysis.

You almost always want to use summary(anova_result) to see the results of your ANOVA.

Understanding R’s aov() Output:

When you run summary() on an object created by aov() (e.g., summary(anova_result)), R displays the results in a standard Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) table. Here’s what each column typically means using your Size ~ Site example:

  • Source Column (Row Labels, e.g., Site, Residuals)

    • This column identifies the sources contributing to the variation in your dependent variable (Size).

    • Site: Represents the variation between the different groups defined by your predictor variable (the different locations).

    • Residuals (or Error): Represents the unexplained variation, or the variation within each of the site groups.

  • Df (Degrees of Freedom)

    • This shows the degrees of freedom associated with each source of variation.

    • For Site: Usually calculated as (number of sites - 1). It reflects the number of independent pieces of information used to estimate the between-group variation.

    • For Residuals: Usually calculated as (total number of observations - number of sites). It reflects the number of independent pieces of information used to estimate the within-group variation (error).

  • Sum Sq (Sum of Squares)

    • This quantifies the amount of variation in the Size variable attributable to each source.

    • Sum Sq for Site: Represents the total variation between the mean sizes of the different sites.

    • Sum Sq for Residuals: Represents the total variation within the site groups (i.e., variation not explained by the site difference)

  • Mean Sq (Mean Square)

    • This is calculated by dividing the Sum of Squares by its corresponding Degrees of Freedom (Sum Sq / Df). It represents the average variation accounted for by that source.

    • Mean Sq for Site: Average variation between site means.

    • Mean Sq for Residuals: Average variation within sites (this is an estimate of the pooled error variance).

  • F value (F-statistic)

    • This is the core test statistic for ANOVA. It’s calculated as the ratio of the Mean Square for the predictor to the Mean Square for the Residuals: Mean Sq (Site) / Mean Sq (Residuals).

    • stats specific info It compares the average variation between groups to the average variation within groups. A larger F value suggests that the variation between the site means is large relative to the variation within the sites, providing evidence against the null hypothesis.

  • Pr(>F) (P-value)

    • This is the probability of observing an F-statistic as large as, or larger than, the one calculated from your sample, assuming that the null hypothesis is actually true (i.e., assuming the true mean Size is the same across all Site populations).

  • Significance Codes (e.g., ***, **, *, .)

    • These are often included next to the p-value as a quick visual guide to the level of statistical significance (e.g., *** usually means p < 0.001, ** means p < 0.01, * means p < 0.05, . means p < 0.1).

NOTICE FOR AN ANOVA IT SIMPLY TELLS YOU IF THERE IS A DIFFERENCE BETWEEN SOME GROUPS BUT WON’T SPECIFY WHICH. You need to run a post-hoc test (Tukey) in order to get all pairwise comparisons to see which are significantly different (in graphs usually represented as letters):

TukeyHSD(anova_result)

Activity #2 : Chi-squared test and bar plots

Objective 1: Perform a chi-squared test to determine if the distribution of fish species is independent of the site where they were observed.

Chi-squared (χ²) tests are used to analyze categorical data.

Specifically, the data that goes into a Chi-squared test consists of counts or frequencies of observations that fall into different categories/groups.

For ease of analysis, let’s filter the data to just 2 species and 4 sites:

species_data3 <- bonaire_fish_counts %>%
    filter(Species %in% c("Stoplight parrotfish",
                          "Ocean surgeonfish",
                          "Redband parrotfish",
                          "Blue tang")) %>%
    filter(Site %in% c("SaltCity", "PinkBeach"))

Now we need to create a contingency table (counts of number of fish at each site):

contingency_table <- table(species_data3$Species, 
                           species_data3$Site)
contingency_table
##                       
##                        PinkBeach SaltCity
##   Blue tang                   26       22
##   Ocean surgeonfish           36       30
##   Redband parrotfish          43       45
##   Stoplight parrotfish        36       51

Syntax for using chisq.test() which is part of Base R:

chisq.test(your_contingency_table)

Using our data:

chi_squared_result <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
chi_squared_result
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  contingency_table
## X-squared = 3.3429, df = 3, p-value = 0.3417

Understanding R’s chisq.test Output:

  • Test Name: (e.g., Pearson's Chi-squared test)

    • Identifies the specific type of Chi-squared test performed.

    • For a two-way contingency table, it’s usually Pearson’s test.

  • data: (e.g., data: contingency_table)

    • Reminds you which data object (your contingency table) was used for the test.

  • X-squared = ... (The Chi-squared statistic)

    • This is the calculated value of the test statistic (often written as χ²).

    • It quantifies the overall difference between your observed counts in the contingency_table and the counts that would be expected if there were truly no association between Species and Site.

    • stats specific info: A larger X-squared value indicates a greater discrepancy between observed and expected counts.

  • df = ... (Degrees of Freedom)

    • reflects the number of independent pieces of information in the table used to calculate the test statistic

    • stats specific info: degrees of freedom for a test of independence on a contingency table are calculated as: (number of rows - 1) * (number of columns - 1)

      • with 4 species (rows) and 2 sites (columns), df = (4 - 1) * (2 - 1) = 3 * 1 = 3

  • Warning Message (Optional)

    • You might see a warning like Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect if any of the expected cell counts are low (often the threshold is < 5). This means the theoretical Chi-squared distribution might not be a good fit for calculating the p-value, and you might consider alternatives like Fisher’s Exact Test (fisher.test()) if appropriate (especially for 2x2 tables or small samples).

The chi_squared_result object stores more detailed information than is printed by default. You can access these components using the $ operator:

chi_squared_result$observed

## df 
##  3
chi_squared_result$p.value
## [1] 0.3417217

  • chi_squared_result$observed:

    • Returns the original contingency table of observed counts that you provided as input.

    • Use: To review the raw counts you tested.

  • chi_squared_result$expected:

    • Returns a table of the expected counts. These are the counts calculated for each cell assuming the null hypothesis (no association) is true.

    • Use: can compare this table cell-by-cell with $observed to see where the biggest differences are. It’s also essential for checking the assumption about low expected frequencies (are any cells < 5?)

  • chi_squared_result$residuals:

    • Returns a table of Pearson residuals. Calculated for each cell as: (Observed - Expected) / sqrt(Expected).

    • Use: Helps identify which cells contribute most to the overall Chi-squared statistic. Cells with larger absolute residual values represent larger deviations from what was expected under the null hypothesis.

  • chi_squared_result$stdres:

    • Returns a table of standardized residuals. These are adjusted versions of the Pearson residuals that account for the margins of the table and approximately follow a standard normal distribution (mean 0, SD 1) if the null hypothesis is true.

    • Use: Often preferred over simple residuals for identifying significant deviations. Absolute values greater than approx. 2 or 3 are often considered indicative of a cell contributing significantly to the rejection of the null hypothesis (i.e., a specific species/site combination that deviates strongly from the expected pattern).

  • chi_squared_result$statistic:

    • the numerical value of the Chi-squared statistic (X-squared).

  • chi_squared_result$parameter:

    • the numerical value of the degrees of freedom (df)

  • chi_squared_result$p.value:

    • the numerical value of the p-value

Objective 1: Perform a linear regression and plot the results

A linear regression looks at the relationship between two numeric variables that have been measured (e.g., size, weight, length, distances)

Because the data I’ve provided doesn’t actually have any good columns to explore a linear relationship, we will create some fake data to play with. Let’s create 100 observations where we have measured distance from a coral patch (distance) and the size of a fish (size)

Syntax for using lm() which is part of Base R:

lm(dependent variable ~ independent variables, data = your_data_frame)

  • dependent_variable ~ predictor_variable1 + predictor_variable2 + ...

    • The tilde (~) separates the dependent (or response) variable (on the left) from the independent (or predictor) variables (on the right).

    • The plus sign (+) is used to include multiple predictor variables in the model.

For our example, we want to investigate how the fish size (dependent/response) is related to distance from the coral patch (independent/predictor):

Understanding R’s lm() Output:

  • Call: lm(formula = Size ~ Distance, data = simulated_data)

    • reminds you of the function call that generated the model, including the formula used and the data source

  • Residuals:

    • Explanation: Residuals are now the differences between the actual observed Size values and the Size values predicted by the model (Observed Size - Predicted Size).

    • What to look for: Ideally, the residuals should be roughly symmetrically distributed around zero (Median close to 0), suggesting the linear model is appropriate and errors are random. Large deviations or asymmetry might indicate issues with the model assumptions.

  • Coefficients:

    • This is the core table showing the estimated model coefficients and their statistical significance.

      • (Intercept) Row:

        • Estimate: The estimated value of the y-intercept (β₀). This is the predicted Size when Distance is equal to 0. Caution: Only interpret this directly if Distance = 0 is a meaningful value within the range of your data.

        • Std. Error: The standard error of the intercept estimate, indicating the uncertainty around the estimated intercept value

        • t value: The t-statistic for testing the null hypothesis that the true intercept is 0 (Estimate / Std. Error).

        • Pr(>|t|): The p-value associated with the t-statistic. A small p-value suggests the intercept is significantly different from zero.

      • Distance Row: (Or your predictor variable’s name)

        • Estimate: The estimated slope coefficient (β₁) for the Distance variable. This represents the estimated change in Size for a one-unit increase in Distsance

        • Std. Error: The standard error of the slope estimate, indicating the uncertainty around the estimated slope value.

        • t value: The t-statistic for testing the null hypothesis that the true slope is 0 (i.e., Distance has no linear relationship with Size). Calculated as Estimate / Std. Error.

        • Pr(>|t|): The p-value for the t-test of the slope. A small p-value (typically < 0.05) indicates that Distance is a statistically significant predictor of Size in your model.

      • Significance codes: The stars (***, **, *, .) provide a quick visual reference for the p-values, indicating levels of statistical significance.

  • Residual standard error:

    • This is an estimate of the standard deviation of the residuals (σ). It represents the typical size of the prediction errors made by the model, measured in the same units as the dependent variable (Size). Smaller values generally indicate a better model fit (less error). The “degrees of freedom” here are the residual degrees of freedom (n - number of parameters, where n is the sample size).

  • Multiple R-squared:

    • AKA: coefficient of determination (R²).

    • measures the proportion of the total variance in the dependent variable (Size) that is explained by the predictor variable(s) (Distance) in the model. It ranges from 0 to 1 (or 0% to 100%). A higher R² indicates that your model explains a larger portion of the variability in Size. Here, 5% of the variance in Size is explained by Distance.

  • Adjusted R-squared:

    • modified version of R² that adjusts for the number of predictors in the model relative to the sample size.

    • penalizes the R² value for adding predictors that don’t significantly improve the model fit

    • useful when comparing models with different numbers of predictors

    • It will always be less than or equal to the Multiple R-squared

  • F-statistic:

    • This line presents the results of an F-test for the overall significance of the model (not by predictor if you have multiple)

    • It tests the null hypothesis that all predictor slope coefficients in the model are simultaneously equal to zero (H₀: β₁ = 0 in this simple case) against the alternative that at least one coefficient is non-zero

    • For simple linear regression (one predictor), the F-test essentially tests the same hypothesis as the t-test for the slope coefficient (for us Distance) (and F = t²)

    • on 1 and 98 DF: Shows the numerator (number of predictors) and denominator (residual) degrees of freedom for the F-test

    • p-value:: The p-value associated with the F-statistic

Graphing for a linear regression

Use geom_smooth() to add a regression line to your scatter plot. It adds a trendline and displays a confidence interval (usually 95%) as a shaded ribbon around the line standard error to your plot:

ggplot(simulated_data, aes(x = Distance, y = Size)) +
    geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "hotpink")+
    theme_classic()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Part 1: For Loops

A for loop is a programming tool that allows you to repeat a set of instructions a specific number of times.

Basic syntax for a for loop:

for (iterator.variable in sequence) {
    # code to be executed
}

  • The word for tells R we’re starting a loop

  • The iterator.variable is like a counter or placeholder that changes each time through the loop

  • The sequence tells R how many times to repeat or what values to use

  • Everything inside the curly braces {} is the code that will be repeated

Example 1: Basic for loops

for (i in 1:5) { 
    print(i) 
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 3
## [1] 4
## [1] 5

What’s happening:

  • 1:5 creates a sequence from 1 to 5

  • i is the iterator variable (like a counter)

  • Each time through the loop, i takes the next value: 1, then 2, then 3, etc.

  • The code inside {} runs once for each value of i

In words: “Take the variable i, give it each value from 1 to 5 in order, and each time print that value.” It’s like saying “Do this thing 5 times, and each time use a different number.”

The ITERATOR VARIABLE is simply a placeholder and it can be WHATEVER YOU WANT IT TO BE, but it needs to be used within the code in brackets.

Each time through the loop, your variable gets updated to the next value in your sequence, allowing you to perform operations with that new value.

Let’s take for instance this example. dobby is our iterator variable (placeholder for the item that changes with each loop) now:

for (dobby in 1:5) {
    print(i)
}
## [1] 5
## [1] 5
## [1] 5
## [1] 5
## [1] 5

In this loop, dobby is the iterator variable that takes on values from 1 to 5.

However, the code attempts to print i, which is not defined within this loop. This results in the loop simply printing whatever value of i is defined in your environment for every iteration of the loop or errors if i was not previously defined.

In R, each for loop creates its own local scope for the iterator variable, and variables outside this scope cannot be accessed unless explicitly defined globally.

The iterator variable dobby should be used inside the loop instead of referencing an undefined variable i.

How can we fix this to be correct?

for (dobby in 1:5) {
    print(dobby)
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 3
## [1] 4
## [1] 5

Here, dobby correctly serves as the iterator variable and is printed during each iteration.

This works as expected because the iterator variable (dobby) is properly referenced within the loop! Yay us :)

The power of for loops comes from their flexibility - you can loop through:

  • Numbers (1:10)

  • Lists of words (c("cat", "dog", "fish"))

  • Data in a spreadsheet (e.g., over rows or over columns or over unique values in column)

  • Any other sequence of items

When I build for loops, I like to start by performing the task for a single (sometimes multiple) item in my sequence. Then I can start to see the steps I need to take for each iteration and where my iterator variable might go.

This is a technique called “concrete to abstract” or “bottom-up” programming. Here’s how it works:

  1. Start with a Concrete Example

    • Instead of immediately trying to write a loop, you first work through the problem with a single item

    • For example, if you’re processing a list of numbers, you’d first write code that handles just one number

  2. Identify the Pattern

    • After working through one or two concrete examples, you’ll start to see the pattern

    • You’ll notice which parts of your code stay the same and which parts change

    • The parts that change are usually where your iterator variable will go

  3. Example: I want to get the square of every number between 1 and 50. I start doing this for each number in my sequence:

    1^2
    ## [1] 1
    2^2
    ## [1] 4
    3^2
    ## [1] 9
    4^2
    ## [1] 16
    5^2
    ## [1] 25
    6^2
    ## [1] 36

What is the same for each line and what is changing in each line?

  • some number in the sequence ^ 2

What is the same will be the code you keep within the brackets - what is changing is the sequence you will iterate over and replace with the iterator variable within the loop:

for (number in 1:50) {
    print(number^2)
}

Here we have replaced the indivdiual number with the iterator variable number and have provided the sequence it will iterate/loop over (1:50).

Let’s take a moment to look at the use of print() within a for loop:

when we just run the code outside of the for loop, we don’t have to tell R to print the result in the console:

number <- 3
number^2
## [1] 9

This will output in the console the number 9.

However, if we attempt to do this within our for loop:

for (number in 1:50) {
   number^2
}

We notice nothing appears in the console. This means the key difference between these two loops:

Example 2: Storing outputs from for loops

If you want to see the output of each iteration of the loop, you need to either print() the result or store them in a vector, dataframe, matrix, or other data structure. We will take our same for loop that squares our number and store it into a vector:

  1. Create the empty vector
empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things <- numeric(50)

  • This creates a numeric vector with 50 elements

  • All elements are initialized to 0 by default

  • The numeric() function is specifically for creating numeric vectors

  • The length (50) is specified in the parentheses

  • This is like creating an empty container with 50 slots, all ready to be filled

  • NOTE: You need to know how long/big you want your vector or output data storage to be

For a vector, you can access a single element of the vector using brackets:

empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things[5]
## [1] 0

This accesses the fifth element of the vector and just returns in the console that value. So

empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things[i]

should return the ith value of the vector

  • NOTE: In R, vector indices start at 1 (unlike some other languages that start at 0)

YOU CREATE THE EMPTY VECTOR OUTSIDE THE FOR LOOP!!

  1. Create the for loop:
empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things <- numeric(50)

for (ella in 1:50) {
   ella^2
}

Now we need to add something that stores each value WITHIN the for loop before it moves to the next iteration:

  1. Add a line within your for loop that stores your value:
empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things <- numeric(50)

for (ella in 1:50) {
    empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things[ella] <- ella^2
}

empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things
##  [1]    1    4    9   16   25   36   49   64   81  100  121  144  169  196  225
## [16]  256  289  324  361  400  441  484  529  576  625  676  729  784  841  900
## [31]  961 1024 1089 1156 1225 1296 1369 1444 1521 1600 1681 1764 1849 1936 2025
## [46] 2116 2209 2304 2401 2500
  • ella is the iterator variable
  • 1:50 creates a sequence from 1 to 50
  • The loop will run 50 times, with ella taking values from 1 to 50

  • Inside the loop:

    • ella^2 calculates the square of the current value of ella
  • empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things[ella] stores this square in the corresponding position of the vector (ellath item)

Break it down:

  • First iteration: ella = 1

    • Calculates 1² = 1

    • Stores 1 in position 1 of the vector

  • Second iteration: ella = 2

    • Calculates 2² = 4

    • Stores 4 in position 2 of the vector

  • And so on until ella = 50

    • Calculates 50² = 2500

    • Stores 2500 in position 50 of the vector

  • After the loop completes, empty_vector_of_cool_NUMERIC_things will contain the squares of numbers 1 through 50

Example 3: For loop over character vector

You don’t have to loop over numbers, you can loop over a vector of strings. Commonly, I loop over some unique value in one of my columns in my data using unique() to create my character string vector.

For this example we first need to learn the function paste() or paste0().

The paste() and paste0() functions in R are used to combine (concatenate) strings together.

  • paste() combines strings with a space as the default separator
  • paste0() combines strings with no separator (hence the “0” in the name)
paste("I", "am cool")    # Returns: "I am cool"
## [1] "I am cool"
paste0("I", "am cool")   # Returns: "Iam cool"
## [1] "Iam cool"

In paste(), you can also specify different separators:

paste("I", "am cool", sep = " ")      # Returns: "I am cool"
## [1] "I am cool"
paste("I", "am cool", sep = "-")      # Returns: "I-am cool"
## [1] "I-am cool"
paste("I", "am cool", sep = "!!!")    # Returns: "I!!!am cool"
## [1] "I!!!am cool"
paste("I", "am cool", sep = "")       # Same as paste0(): "Iam cool"
## [1] "Iam cool"

You can also paste with stored variables that are both character strings and numeric. Notice that because it is a named item in our environment, we don’t need to put it them quotations marks:

name <- "Dobby"
age <- 14
paste("My sweet baby girl", name, "is turning", age, "years old next week!", sep = " ")
## [1] "My sweet baby girl Dobby is turning 14 years old next week!"
# Returns: "My sweet baby girl Dobby is turning 14 years old next week!"

Back to for loops! We can create a character string to loop over:

animals <- c("cat", "dog", "bird", "fish")

for (pets in animals) {
   
   print(paste("I have a", pets))
    
}
## [1] "I have a cat"
## [1] "I have a dog"
## [1] "I have a bird"

What’s happening?

  • pets takes each value from the animals vector in order

Part 2: If-Else Statements

Basic syntaxes for if-else statements:

# === BASIC IF STATEMENT SYNTAX ===
if (condition) {
    # code to execute if condition is TRUE
}



# === IF-ELSE SYNTAX ===
if (condition) {
    # code to execute if condition is TRUE
} else {
    # code to execute if condition is FALSE
}



# === IF-ELSE IF-ELSE SYNTAX ===
if (condition1) {
    # code for condition1
} else if (condition2) {
    # code for condition2
} else {
    # code if no conditions are TRUE
}

Key Points to Remember:

  • Condition Requirements:

    • Must evaluate to TRUE or FALSE

    • Cannot evaluate to NA (this will cause an error)

    • Can combine multiple conditions with logical operators

  • Code Block Structure:

    • Use curly braces {} just like in for loop statements

Example 1: Simple IF statements

These simple if statements only execute code if the condition evaluates to TRUE, meaning nothing happens (no output) if the condition evaluates to FALSE

What I mean when I say a condition needs to evaluate to TRUE or FALSE:

temperature <- 31
temperature > 30 ## when the variable temperature is equal to 31, this phrase (condition) evaluates to TRUE betwen 31 > 30
## [1] TRUE
temperature <- 29
temperature > 30 ## when the variable temperature is equal to 29, this phrase (condition) evaluates to FALSE betwen 29 < 30
## [1] FALSE

These logical comparisons (>, <, ==, etc.) return TRUE or FALSE based on whether the condition is met.

TYPES OF CONDITIONS

Can have 1 condition:

# Equal to
if (x == 5) {}
# Not equal to
if (x != 4) {}
# Greater than
if (x > 3) {}
# Less than
if (x < 6) {}
# Greater than or equal to
if (x >= 5) {}
# Less than or equal to
if (x <= 5) {}
## the value is NA
if (is.na(x)) {}
## the value is not NA
if (!is.na(x)) {}
# Using %in% for multiple values
if (x %in% some_vector_with_multiple_values) {}

Can use logical operators to have multiple conditions:

# AND operator ( &)
# both of these conditions must evaluate to TRUE in order for the code to execute, meaning both x needs to be greater than 5 AND y needs to be greater than 7
if (x > 5 & y > 7) {}

# OR operator ( |)
# only one of these conditions must evaluate to TRUE in order for the code to execute, meaning EITHER x < 5 OR x > 10 
if (x < 5 | x > 10) {}

Let’s look at a simple if statement:

temperature <- 29

if(temperature > 30){
    print("It's blazin today")
}

this is:

  • checking if the `temperature` variable is above 30
  • If TRUE, it prints a message
  • If FALSE, it prints nothing (it doesn’t evaluate)

Notice that in how we writing this, that temperature must be created prior to the condition being executed. R needs to know what temperature is before it can compare it to 30 - so we know that the variable involved in our condition has to exists in our environment somewhere, either in a vector or df in order to evaluate.

Example:

# Wrong order - will cause error because value isn't previously stored in the environment
if(value > 5) {
    print("Your value is greater than 5")
}
value <- 77

# Correct order
value <- 77
if(value > 5) {
    print("Your value is greater than 5")
}

Example 2: Simple IF-ELSE statements

Let’s add on to our temperature for loop so that we have a response when the condition evaluates to FALSE:

temperature <- 25

if (temperature > 30) {
    print("It's blazin today")
} else {
    print("It's so cold I have frostbite")
}
## [1] "It's so cold I have frostbite"

This code provides two paths of execution based on the same condition: either the if code block will run if the condition is TRUE or the else code block will run if the condition is FALSE .

You do NOT provide another condition in a simple if-else statement, you simply put the code to execute if the original condition is FALSE

Note - you MUST put the else on the same line as the ending bracket of the if statement

For our other example:

value <- 77
if(value > 5) {
    print("Your value is greater than 5")
} else {
    print("Your value is lower than 5")
}
## [1] "Your value is greater than 5"

With how we have this written, what happens when value <- 5 ?

Well, when the value is 5:

  • The condition value > 5 evaluates to FALSE (because 5 is not greater than 5)
  • Therefore, the else block executes

So what if we want to account for a situation where we have a special output if our value is specifically 5?

Example 3: Simple IF-ELSE IF-ELSE statements

In if-else if-else statements, you have two conditions to provide, and it evaluates those conditions from top to bottom (order of the conditions matters):

value <- 5

if(value > 5) {
    print("Your value is greater than 5")
} else if(value < 5) {
    print("Your value is less than 5")
} else {
    print("Your value is exactly than 5")
}
## [1] "Your value is exactly than 5"

What’s happening when value <- 5:

  • First condition value > 5 is FALSE so it moves to the next condition provided by the else if
  • Second condition value < 5 is FALSE so it moves to the final else
  • The final else block executes and so the output will be "Your value is exactly than 5"

Let’s look at our temperature example again:

temperature <- 25

if(temperature > 30) {
    print("It's blazin!")
} else if(temperature > 20) {
    print("It's warm-hot")
} else if(temperature > 10) {
    print("It's a temperature I won't complain about")
} else {
    print("I have frostbite")
}
## [1] "It's warm-hot"

Notice - you can have multiple else if statements stacked. Remember, the else if statements provide additional conditions to check, and here the else statement evaluates only when all the conditions provided evaluate to FALSE

But what happens if we put it in the wrong (illogical) order?

temperature <- 25

if(temperature > 10) {
    print("It's a temperature I won't complain about")
} else if(temperature > 20) {
    print("It's warm-hot")  # This will never be reached when temperature is equal to 25 because the first condition evaluated to TRUE
} else if(temperature > 30) {
    print("It's blazin!")  # This will never be reached!
} else {
    print("I have frostbite")
}
## [1] "It's a temperature I won't complain about"
# Output: "It's a temperature I won't complain about"

What’s wrong here?

  • First condition temperature > 10 is TRUE (25 > 10)

  • The code executes that block and stops

  • The other conditions are never checked, even though they might also be TRUE

  • We get the wrong output because the conditions are in the wrong order

Part 3: Number guessing game example

# Define a function that creates a simple number guessing game
number_guessing_game <- function() {
    
    # Generate a random target number between 1 and 10
    target <- sample(1:10, 1)  
    
    # Loop to give the player 3 attempts to guess the number
    for (i in 1:3) {  
        # Prompt the player for their guess and convert it to a number
        guess <- as.numeric(readline("Guess a number between 1 and 10: "))
        
        # Check if the guess matches the target number
        if (guess == target) {
            print("You won! Dobby is pleased!")
            return()  # Exit the function immediately if the guess is correct
        } 
        # If guess is lower than the target number
        else if (guess < target) {
            print("Too low! Dobby suggests you guess a higher number!")
        } 
        # If guess is higher than the target number
        else {
            print("Too high! Dobby suggests you guess a lower number!")
        }
    }
    
    # This line only executes if the player used all 3 guesses without winning
    print(paste("Game over! The number was", target))
}

number_guessing_game() ##executes the code to play the game

Some explanation:

  • function()

    • Creates a reusable block of code
    -   we will talk about functions at a later week

  • sample(1:10, 1)

    • Randomly selects one number from 1 to 10

  • for (i in 1:3)

    • Creates a loop that runs 3 times (i=1, then i=2, then finally i=3

  • readline()

    • Gets input from the user

    • In detail this function first pauses program execution, then displays a prompt in the console to the user, then waits for the user to type an input, and then returns what the use typed as a character string (which is then why it needs to be converted to a numeric variable

  • as.numeric() - Converts the user’s input to a number

  • return()

    • Exits the function immediately, this command is specific to creating functions

  • paste()

    • Combines text with the target number for the game over message
